		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Mon, May 24th 8:11 AM2004 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/db/classes.html?class=8&mid=107845432730450&num=6&post=1&replyto=1085400614426893761"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>  | <a class=sm href="mailto:newgenhardheart@allakhazam.com"><img src="/shared/mail3.gif" border="0" height="10" width="17" /> Email User</a>  <a name=1085400614426893761></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=69700"><span id=Scholar>newgenhardheart</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />69 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.25]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=newgenhardheart&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Quading mobs is one of best ways to get fast experience in game.<br><br>I used to practice on giant spiders in West Commonlands prior to level 34, just to get proficient at grouping the mobs.&nbsp;&nbsp;You need space to kite and the best way to learn to group the mobs is using third person view.  When you first do this, you will have trouble changing the view as you run around.  In addition, in quading, you need to be fairly close to the mobs and the third person does not give you 3D ability and mobs can be much closer than they look unless you rotate the view. An optical mouse helps greatly, also.<br><br>One item that helps me greatly in switching views is a mouse with additional buttons that can be programmed.  Having one button that switches to third person view and another to restore first person view is most helpful.<br><br>Most mobs you quad when starting out will kill you very quickly if you ever drop SoW or get stunned.  Keeping Snare, root, and SoW up at all times will save you many times.<br><br>When done correctly, you can quad 4 red mobs at a time.  Imagine the experience!  In addition, if you need quick cash, I have always found spider silks to be very lucrative.  I quad the crag spiders in East Karana, and they drop as many as 7 or 8 silks at a time.  Selling them for 10-15 pp each in bazaar will do wonders for your bank account.  This is a difficult zone to quad due to some of the adds, and by the time you can quad spiders you won't get a lot of experience, but keep it in your repetoire (tis a small mind that admits of a single way to spell a word).<br><br>Another word of caution:  Druids sometimes get a bad name for quading in areas where they intrude on other peoples kite paths and camping areas.  Always be thoughtful, and if one of your pulls intrudes, at the very least apologize, and heal, or do whatever you can do to help them recover.  When you are kiting red mobs 4 at a time, they pose a very significant danger to bystanders.  You should chose a death before allowing your pull to harm others, especially if they are lower levels.<br><br>Be prepared for snide comments and complaints. Other players who can barely manage to solo mobs do not like watching a lower level druid quad a mob where they can see it happen.  Some of this is jealousy, but some of it is honest competition.  Don't get into shouting matches or name calling.  I often shout and offer free SoW's and this greatly helps your relations with other players.  You will be surprised how often good friends are found in this manner.  A druid who quad kites effectively, but has respect for all the other players is welcome in any zone.<br><br>Here are some good targets for Quad kiting:<br>1-Spirocs in the Timorous Deep.  Bind far away from the Spiroc Camp so you can port out to sell and come back without boarding the boat.  Most times you will have the camp to yourself.<br>2-Wyverns in Cobalt Scar.  Make sure you have good Claws of Veeshan faction.  Useless to try until you do, or the drakes will make you life unbelievably painful.  To get it, kill the giants and wolves in Great Divide or Kael Drakkel.  You can easily quad wyverns on top of the plateau, but be careful you don't pull the named wyvern, his faction hit is very bad.  If you quad too close to him, he will aggro, and is immune to run speed changes (bad, very bad) so you need to forget your quad and boogie outta there ASAP!<br>3-Raptors in Timorous Deep.  There are several posts on these, so I won't repeat.  I didn't find these all that good because I got there when I was past the prime level for quading them, but if you get there at right time I am sure they're great.  These are really dangerous though, so be prepared for a long CR if you let your guard down.<br><br>Hope that helps.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td><td align="right" id="fs8" >0 Replies</td></tr></table>
